A dung beetle is a type of insect that belongs to the family Scarabaeidae. 
They are typically small in size and have a rounded, oval-shaped body. 
Their coloring can vary from black and brown to metallic shades of blue and green. 
Their wings are often hidden under hard, protective shells that cover their bodies. 
Dung beetles are named after their primary food source, which is animal dung. 
They are important decomposers in ecosystems, as they help break down animal waste. 
Dung beetles can be found in various habitats, including forests, grasslands, and deserts.
